By calculating \( P(n) \) for small values of \( n \), we observe a pattern: - \( P(1) = \frac{1}{2} \) - \( P(2) = \frac{1}{2} \) - \( P(3) = \frac{1}{2} \) - \( P(4) = \frac{1}{2} \) - \( P(5) = \frac{1}{2} \) This pattern continues for all \( n \geq 1 \). To confirm this, we use generating functions. The generating function \( G(x) \) for the sequence \( P(n) \) is derived and simplified to: \[ G(x) = \frac{2 - x}{2(1 - x)} \] Expanding this generating function, we find that the coefficient of \( x^n \) for \( n \geq 1 \) is \( \frac{1}{2} \), confirming that \( P(n) = \frac{1}{2} \) for all \( n \geq 1 \). Thus, the probability that Flora will eventually land at 10 is \( \frac{1}{2} \). The fraction \( \frac{1}{2} \) simplifies to \( \frac{1}{2} \), and the sum of the numerator and denominator is \( 1 + 2 = 3 \). \[ \boxed{3} \]
